# **50 Top System Design Concepts Developers Must Understand**

## Understand the 50 essential system design terminologies before your interview.

![][image3]  
50 System Design Concepts Developers Must Understand

Let us be honest: [System design concepts](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/system-design-interview-fundamentals) are not that simple to understand.

Most terminologies can be intimidating, especially if you’re just starting.

Whether you’re preparing for a system design interview at a top tech company or looking to enhance your ability to build robust applications, you have no choice but to have a solid grasp of these concepts.

For this reason, I have shortlisted **50 top system design terminologies** and I will you walk through the fundamentals in this guide.

# **1\. Latency**

Latency refers to the time delay between a request being sent and the corresponding response being received. Lower latency means faster response times, which is crucial for user satisfaction.

# **2\. Throughput**

Throughput measures the number of requests a system can handle within a specific time frame. High throughput is essential for systems with heavy traffic.

# **3\. Load Balancer**

**![][image4]**  
Load Balancer

A [load balancer](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/load-balancer-reverse-proxy-api-gateway) distributes incoming network traffic across multiple servers to ensure no single server becomes overwhelmed. This enhances availability and reliability.

# **4\. Caching**

**![][image5]**  
Caching

[Caching](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/caching-system-design-interview) involves storing frequently accessed data in a temporary storage layer to speed up retrieval times and reduce server load. Common caching systems include Redis and Memcached.

# **5\. Database Sharding**

[Sharding](https://medium.com/codex/grokking-system-design-what-is-database-sharding-97830014baab) splits a large database into smaller, more manageable pieces called shards, which are stored across different servers. This improves [scalability](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/grokking-system-design-scalability) and performance.

# **6\. Indexing**

Indexing creates a data structure that allows for faster data retrieval. Proper indexing is crucial for optimizing database queries and improving performance.

# **7\. CAP Theorem**

The [CAP Theorem](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/system-design-interview-basics-cap-vs-pacelc) states that in distributed systems, you can achieve only two out of three guarantees: Consistency, Availability, and Partition Tolerance. Understanding this helps in making informed design decisions.

![][image6]  
CAP Theorem

# **8\. Replication**

Replication involves creating multiple copies of data across different servers to ensure data availability and fault tolerance. This enhances reliability in case of server failures.

# **9\. Consistency Models**

[Consistency models](https://levelup.gitconnected.com/i-wish-i-knew-these-data-consistency-concepts-before-the-system-design-interview-207f9bed4c0a) define how data is kept consistent across distributed systems. Common models include strong consistency, eventual consistency, and causal consistency.

# **10\. Message Queue**

A message queue allows different parts of a system to communicate asynchronously by sending and receiving messages. Examples include RabbitMQ and Apache Kafka.

# **11\. Microservices**

**![][image7]**  
Microservices Architecture

[Microservices architecture](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/monolithic-service-oriented-microservice-architecture) breaks down an application into smaller, independent services that communicate over a network. This enhances scalability and maintainability.

# **12\. Monolithic Architecture**

A [monolithic architecture](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/monolithic-service-oriented-microservice-architecture) combines all components of an application into a single, unified codebase. While simpler to develop initially, it can become challenging to scale.

# **13\. API Gateway**

An [API Gateway](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/load-balancer-reverse-proxy-api-gateway) acts as a single entry point for all client requests, routing them to the appropriate backend services. It also handles tasks like authentication and rate limiting.

# **14\. Rate Limiting**

Rate limiting controls the number of requests a user can make to an API within a specific time period, preventing abuse and ensuring fair usage.

# **15\. Data Partitioning**

Data partitioning divides data into smaller, manageable chunks that can be distributed across multiple servers. This improves performance and scalability.

![][image8]  
Horizontal vs. vertical data partitioning

# **16\. Leader Election**

Leader election is the process of selecting a leader node in a distributed system to coordinate tasks and manage resources efficiently.

# **17\. Eventual Consistency**

Eventual consistency ensures that all replicas of data will become consistent over time, even if they are temporarily out of sync. This is common in distributed databases.

# **18\. Failover**

Failover is the process of switching to a backup system or server when the primary one fails, ensuring continuous service availability.

# **19\. ACID Transactions**

ACID stands for Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability. These properties ensure reliable and secure database transactions.

# **20\. BASE Properties**

BASE stands for Basically Available, Soft state, and Eventually consistent. It provides a more flexible approach compared to ACID, suitable for distributed systems.

# **21\. Load Shedding**

Load shedding reduces system load by temporarily refusing low-priority requests during high traffic periods, maintaining overall performance.

# **22\. Proxy Server**

A [proxy server](https://www.designgurus.io/answers/detail/what-is-the-difference-between-proxy-and-reverse-proxy) acts as an intermediary between clients and servers, providing benefits like improved security and caching.

# **23\. NoSQL Database**

[NoSQL databases](https://medium.com/geekculture/choosing-the-right-database-for-system-design-sql-vs-nosql-and-beyond-d58fde5a6fe3) handle unstructured or semi-structured data, offering flexibility and scalability. Examples include MongoDB and Cassandra.

# **24\. SQL Database**

**![][image9]**  
SQL vs. NoSQL database

[SQL databases](https://medium.com/geekculture/choosing-the-right-database-for-system-design-sql-vs-nosql-and-beyond-d58fde5a6fe3) use structured query language for defining and manipulating data. They are ideal for applications requiring complex queries and transactions. Examples include MySQL and PostgreSQL.

# **25\. Data Compression**

Data compression reduces the size of data to save storage space and speed up data transfer. Common algorithms include gzip and Brotli.

# **26\. Heartbeat**

A heartbeat is a regular signal sent between servers to confirm they are functioning correctly, helping to detect failures quickly.

# **27\. Sticky Sessions**

Sticky sessions ensure that a user’s requests are always routed to the same server, maintaining session continuity and improving user experience.

# **28\. Circuit Breaker**

A circuit breaker prevents a system from repeatedly trying to execute a failing operation, protecting the system from cascading failures.

# **29\. Quorum**

A quorum is the minimum number of nodes that must agree on a decision in a distributed system, ensuring data consistency and reliability.

# **30\. Event-Driven Architecture**

Event-driven architecture designs systems where components communicate by producing and consuming events, enhancing scalability and responsiveness.

# **31\. Backpressure**

Backpressure is a mechanism to slow down data production when consumers cannot keep up, preventing system overload.

# **32\. Service Discovery**

Service discovery automatically detects and connects services within a network, facilitating communication in microservices architectures.

# **33\. Idempotency**

Idempotency ensures that multiple identical requests have the same effect as a single request, enhancing reliability in APIs.

# **34\. Data Denormalization**

Data denormalization involves duplicating data to improve read performance, reducing the need for complex joins in databases.

# **35\. Strong Consistency**

Strong consistency ensures that all reads return the latest write, maintaining data accuracy across the system.

# **36\. Eventual Consistency**

**![][image10]**  
Strong vs. Weak Consistency

Eventual consistency allows temporary discrepancies in data, with the guarantee that all replicas will eventually be consistent.

# **37\. Tail Latency**

Tail latency measures the slowest response times in a system, focusing on improving the worst-case performance to enhance user experience.

# **38\. Leader-Follower Replication**

Leader-follower replication designates one server as the leader for handling write operations, while followers replicate the data for read operations, ensuring high availability.

![][image11]  
Leader-Follower Replication

# **39\. Consensus Algorithm**

Consensus algorithms ensure that distributed systems agree on a single value or decision, maintaining consistency. Examples include Paxos and Raft.

# **40\. Distributed Hash Table (DHT)**

A DHT stores key-value pairs across multiple nodes in a distributed system, enabling efficient data retrieval in peer-to-peer networks.

# **41\. Content Delivery Network (CDN)**

A [CDN](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/best-5-ways-to-reduce-latency) distributes content across geographically dispersed servers, reducing latency and improving load times for users worldwide.

# **42\. Throttling**

Throttling limits the rate at which an API can be called, preventing abuse and ensuring system stability.

# **43\. Horizontal Scaling**

[Horizontal scaling](https://www.designgurus.io/blog/horizontally-scale-sql-databases) involves adding more servers to handle increased load, enhancing the system’s capacity and reliability.

# **44\. Vertical Scaling**

Vertical scaling increases the resources of a single server (e.g., CPU, RAM) to handle more load, improving performance without adding more machines.

# **45\. Token-Based Authentication**

Token-based authentication uses tokens to verify users, enhancing security by avoiding the need to store session information on the server.

# **46\. Autoscaling**

Autoscaling automatically adjusts the number of active servers based on current demand, ensuring optimal performance and cost-efficiency.

# **47\. Distributed Cache**

A distributed cache stores data across multiple servers, improving data access speed and reducing the load on primary databases.

# **48\. Reverse Proxy**

A [reverse proxy](https://www.designgurus.io/answers/detail/what-is-the-difference-between-proxy-and-reverse-proxy) forwards client requests to backend servers, providing benefits like load balancing, security, and caching.  
Forward Proxy vs. Reverse Proxy

# **49\. Data Serialization**

Data serialization converts data into a format suitable for storage or transmission, enabling efficient data exchange between systems. Common formats include JSON and Protocol Buffers.

# **50\. Domain Name System (DNS)**

DNS translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses, directing traffic to the appropriate servers and ensuring users reach the correct website.
